{
  "doc_id": "49665",
  "text": "Specific types of human papillomaviruses (HPV) are recognized as the major etiological factor in cervical neoplasia [CITATION_1] . In preinvasive lesions, the viral genomes are present as episomal molecules in the nucleus of infected cells. In most cases of invasive carcinoma, however, HPV DNA sequences are integrated into the cellular genome [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Viral genome integration thus represents a crucial step in tumorigenesis [CITATION_5] . A single unique viral integration site has been found in more than 80% of cervical cancers [CITATION_6] .",
